racts—how it distorts credit transactions, suits for damages, and laws of taxation—and he tells how current economic practices can be adapted to reduce or eliminate the impact. He explores the possibility of using a comprehensive indexation scheme for coping with inflation. Although Rosenn recognizes the deficiencies of price indexes, he considers the practical and theoretical implications of indexation. His analysis is firmly grounded in a detailed examination of the experience of countries like Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Finland, France, Germany, Israel, and Italy in adapting their legal institutions to the fact of inflation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInflation (Finance). 0aMoneyxLaw and legislation. 7aLAW / Business & Financial.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280902240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512809022423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781512809022.jpg  a978-3-11-044252-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK